1
00:00:00,700 --> 00:00:05,430
When you’re trading supply and demand zones,
I bet you use classic candlestick charts.

2
00:00:05,430 --> 00:00:10,110
But here’s an idea: what if you used Heiken
Ashi candles?

3
00:00:10,110 --> 00:00:11,790
Would it improve your results?

4
00:00:11,790 --> 00:00:13,749
100% yes.

5
00:00:13,749 --> 00:00:19,330
Today I’m showing you my unique way to trade
supply and demand areas, without noise, using

6
00:00:21,092 --> 00:00:26,782
The only reason why price moves in any market
is because of an imbalance in supply and demand.

7
00:00:26,782 --> 00:00:29,712
The greater the imbalance, the greater the
move.

8
00:00:29,712 --> 00:00:33,752
A strong uptrend can only exist if buyers
outnumber sellers.

9
00:00:33,752 --> 00:00:39,792
During a trend, price moves up until enough
sellers enter the market to absorb the buy

10
00:00:39,792 --> 00:00:40,792
orders.

11
00:00:40,792 --> 00:00:46,072
The origin of strong bullish trends is called
an accumulation or a demand zone.

12
00:00:46,072 --> 00:00:49,672
Bearish trends are created when sellers outnumber
buy orders.

13
00:00:49,672 --> 00:00:55,912
Then, price falls until a new balance is created
and buyers become interested again.

14
00:00:55,912 --> 00:01:00,902
The origin of a bearish trend wave is called
a distribution or a supply zone.

15
00:01:00,902 --> 00:01:06,592
A Demand Zone is a price area below the current
price action where there is strong buying

16
00:01:06,592 --> 00:01:07,861
interest.

17
00:01:07,861 --> 00:01:12,592
Looking at this chart, we can see that there
was a lot of buying interest at this demand

18
00:01:12,592 --> 00:01:13,592
zone.

19
00:01:13,592 --> 00:01:18,421
For this reason, when the price reaches the
level, you will notice a sharp price reaction

20
00:01:18,421 --> 00:01:20,391
from the Demand Zone.

21
00:01:20,391 --> 00:01:23,561
The Supply Zone is the exact opposite of the
Demand Zone.

22
00:01:23,561 --> 00:01:28,751
A Supply area is located above the price action
and it typically contains a relatively big

23
00:01:28,751 --> 00:01:30,901
volume of sell orders.

24
00:01:30,901 --> 00:01:35,511
When the price action reaches this level,
the price reverses to the downside.

25
00:01:35,511 --> 00:01:38,721
Now, let’s introduce Heiken Ashi into equation.

26
00:01:38,721 --> 00:01:43,361
Heikin Ashi has proven to be one of the best
strategies to use to gain a deeper view of

27
00:01:43,361 --> 00:01:48,571
the market, because with these tools it’s
easier to read candlestick charts and analyze

28
00:01:48,571 --> 00:01:50,561
market trends.

29
00:01:50,561 --> 00:01:55,361
Traders use the Heikin Ashi to get information
such as when to stay in a trend trade or if

30
00:01:55,361 --> 00:01:58,181
it’s time to get out because the trend has
reversed.

31
00:01:58,181 --> 00:02:03,142
I don’t want to insist too much on this
topic, as I have several videos on this channel

32
00:02:03,142 --> 00:02:05,922
explaining how these candlesticks work.

33
00:02:05,922 --> 00:02:12,042
Just remember that Heikin Ashi filter noise
and help you to see trend better.

34
00:02:12,042 --> 00:02:15,702
So why trading supply and demand areas using
Heiken Ashi?

35
00:02:15,702 --> 00:02:21,062
As you know, the candles on traditional candlestick
chart usually change from green to red, making

36
00:02:21,062 --> 00:02:23,831
it difficult for some traders to read them
properly.

37
00:02:23,831 --> 00:02:29,462
However, the candles on a Heikin Ashi chart
display more consecutive colored candles,

38
00:02:29,462 --> 00:02:35,362
making it easy for traders to identify past
price movements, current trends and of course,

39
00:02:35,362 --> 00:02:36,572
supply and demand zones.

40
00:02:36,572 --> 00:02:41,851
With Heikin Ashi, trends usually stay green
in an uptrend and red in a downtrend.

41
00:02:41,851 --> 00:02:48,312
For me personally, is much easier to find
supply and demand areas using these candles.

42
00:02:48,312 --> 00:02:52,631
This isn’t the case with the traditional
candlestick charts where colors are different

43
00:02:52,631 --> 00:02:55,422
even if the price is moving strongly in one
direction.

44
00:02:55,422 --> 00:03:01,002
How do you mark a supply and demand zone using
Heiken Ashi?

45
00:03:01,002 --> 00:03:06,292
The idea is to find the place on the chart
where demand overcame supply (for long trades)

46
00:03:06,292 --> 00:03:09,902
or where supply overcame demand (for short
trades).

47
00:03:09,902 --> 00:03:16,182
STEP 1: Identify current market price
STEP 2: Look left on the chart

48
00:03:16,182 --> 00:03:20,232
STEP 3: Look for big green or big red Heiken
ashi candles

49
00:03:20,232 --> 00:03:29,232
STEP 4: Find the origin of the big candles
STEP 5: Mark the zone around this ‘origin’

50
00:03:29,232 --> 00:03:33,822
Since the Heiken Ashi candles start from the
middle of the previous candle, I had to come

51
00:03:33,822 --> 00:03:39,732
up with a slightly different way to mark these
areas, compared to classic candles.

52
00:03:39,732 --> 00:03:44,572
For a supply zone, I search the last BULLISH
Heiken Ashi candle before the drop.

53
00:03:44,572 --> 00:03:50,042
Once you’ve done this, you need to drag
a rectangle up to the most recent high before

54
00:03:50,042 --> 00:04:01,051
the drop.

55
00:04:01,051 --> 00:04:17,692
For a demand zone, I look for the most recent
BEARISH candle before the up move and drag

56
00:04:17,692 --> 00:04:43,692
a rectangle down to the most recent low before
the up move.

57
00:04:43,692 --> 00:04:48,322
Supply and demand levels can be:
• Fresh: It means price has not pulled back

58
00:04:48,322 --> 00:04:54,412
yet, it’s an untested level
• Non-fresh: Price has pulled back to it

59
00:04:54,412 --> 00:04:58,982
at least once
• Used up: Price has pulled back to level

60
00:04:58,982 --> 00:05:05,822
several times, and these are not good for
trading full swings, maybe some scalping trades

61
00:05:05,822 --> 00:05:09,762
Plotting these areas should be done with a
logical and organized approach.

62
00:05:09,762 --> 00:05:14,812
Often, supply and demand traders tend to pollute
charts with tens of levels, where the whole

63
00:05:14,812 --> 00:05:18,752
meaning of anticipating the rejections loses
the value.

64
00:05:18,752 --> 00:05:21,692
So try to keep your charts clean.

65
00:05:21,692 --> 00:05:26,402
When it comes to efficient plotting of supply
and demand zones on the Heiken Ashi chart,

66
00:05:26,402 --> 00:05:31,532
here are main variables that you should follow,
which will increase your efficiency a lot:

67
00:05:31,532 --> 00:05:36,562
-focus on the freshest supply and demand zones
-focus on the strongest zones, those where

68
00:05:36,562 --> 00:05:42,742
price left the zone in a quick, strong move
-focus on nearest zones, so do not plot 50

69
00:05:42,742 --> 00:05:47,362
levels on charts, have only the nearest ones
in sight to keep the chart clean

70
00:05:47,362 --> 00:05:52,742
-focus as much as possible on dense zones
where the price was consolidating for a while

71
00:05:52,742 --> 00:05:55,322
before forming zone

72
00:05:55,322 --> 00:06:00,472
The fresh zone always has priority over the
old historical supply or demand zone because

73
00:06:00,472 --> 00:06:06,302
the statistical chance for order flow to be
still participating in the fresh zone is higher

74
00:06:06,302 --> 00:06:08,662
than in the old historical zone.

75
00:06:08,662 --> 00:06:13,912
As the time passes, the traders will slowly
liquidate positions over time, that is the

76
00:06:13,912 --> 00:06:14,912
fact.

77
00:06:14,912 --> 00:06:18,932
Thus the fresher the zone, the more focus
the trader should put on it.

78
00:06:18,932 --> 00:06:24,822
Personally, I only draw 3 to a maximum of
5 zones on chart at most, on different time

79
00:06:24,822 --> 00:06:27,662
frames, no more than that.

80
00:06:27,662 --> 00:06:32,662
Now let me show you how you find the best
supply and demand Heiken Ashi zone to trade.

81
00:06:32,662 --> 00:06:33,732
I look for several clues:

82
00:06:33,732 --> 00:06:34,732
1.

83
00:06:34,732 --> 00:06:37,902
STRENGTH OF SUPPLY AND DEMAND ZONE
First, you determine the STRENGTH OF THE MOVE.

84
00:06:37,902 --> 00:06:39,812
How did price leave the level?

85
00:06:39,812 --> 00:06:44,572
The stronger the price moves away from a zone,
the more out-of-balance supply and demand

86
00:06:44,572 --> 00:06:46,312
are at that zone.

87
00:06:46,312 --> 00:06:49,252
It means a heavy order is placed by smart
money.

88
00:06:49,252 --> 00:06:53,032
Here’s an example showing different types
of zones.

89
00:06:53,032 --> 00:06:58,082
The first one is the strongest, with large
bearish candles forming after the price left

90
00:06:58,082 --> 00:06:59,552
the area.

91
00:06:59,552 --> 00:07:04,992
The second one is a strong zone, with big
Heiken Ashi candles with no upper wicks and

92
00:07:04,992 --> 00:07:07,372
a few candles having wicks.

93
00:07:07,372 --> 00:07:13,092
And the third one is a weak zone, price moving
down in an unconvincing manner.

94
00:07:13,092 --> 00:07:32,042
This is very powerful, so please remember
this part.

95
00:07:32,042 --> 00:07:48,452
2.

96
00:07:48,452 --> 00:07:51,092
TIME AT SUPPLY AND DEMAND LEVEL

97
00:07:51,092 --> 00:07:54,082
How much time did the price spend at the zone?

98
00:07:54,082 --> 00:07:58,882
The less time price spends at a zone, the
more out-of-balance supply and demand are

99
00:07:58,882 --> 00:08:00,622
at that price level.

100
00:08:00,622 --> 00:08:03,962
This means Smart money are aggressively entering.

101
00:08:03,962 --> 00:08:10,022
The first example is the strongest zone, with
one bearish candle rejecting the area.

102
00:08:10,022 --> 00:08:15,122
The second one is a strong zone, with several
Heiken Ashi inside the zone.

103
00:08:15,122 --> 00:08:20,412
And the third one is a weak zone, with many
candles and a lot of time spent around this

104
00:08:20,412 --> 00:08:36,632
area.

105
00:08:36,632 --> 00:08:52,862
3.

106
00:08:52,862 --> 00:08:58,562
THE MOVE AWAY FROM THE SUPPLY AND DEMAND LEVEL
Here you analyze how far did the price move

107
00:08:58,562 --> 00:09:02,622
away from the zone before returning back around
the area?

108
00:09:02,622 --> 00:09:07,582
The longer the distance the price moves away
from a zone before returning to that zone,

109
00:09:07,582 --> 00:09:11,102
the greater the reward to risk and probability.

110
00:09:11,102 --> 00:09:15,642
When price goes from selling off to a strong
bullish trend for example, there had to be

111
00:09:15,642 --> 00:09:21,312
a significant amount of buy interest entering
the market, absorbing sell orders AND then

112
00:09:21,312 --> 00:09:23,292
driving price higher.

113
00:09:23,292 --> 00:09:44,272
Always look for extremely strong turning points;
these are the high probability price levels.

114
00:09:44,272 --> 00:10:00,652
4.

115
00:10:00,652 --> 00:10:05,732
FRESHNESS OF BASE
Number one rule in supply and demand trading:

116
00:10:05,732 --> 00:10:09,952
First-time retrace to the base is the strongest
to enter.

117
00:10:09,952 --> 00:10:14,452
If you trade of supply areas, always make
sure the zone is still “fresh” which means

118
00:10:14,452 --> 00:10:19,832
that after the initial creation of the zone,
price has not come back to it yet.

119
00:10:19,832 --> 00:10:26,042
Each time price revisits a supply zone, more
and more previously unfilled orders are filled

120
00:10:26,042 --> 00:10:28,902
and the level is weakened continuously.

121
00:10:28,902 --> 00:10:33,712
This is also true for support and resistance
trading where levels get weaker with each

122
00:10:33,712 --> 00:11:06,142
following bounce.

123
00:11:06,142 --> 00:11:10,152
The rules of supply and demand trading using
Heikin Ashi are simple.

124
00:11:10,152 --> 00:11:15,052
You should buy when the price action approaches
a demand level and bounces upwards forming

125
00:11:15,052 --> 00:11:19,002
a green Heiken Ashi candle, ideally with no
lower wick.

126
00:11:19,002 --> 00:11:23,132
You expect the price to increase and you want
to trade an upcoming price swing.

127
00:11:23,132 --> 00:11:28,492
And you should sell when the price reaches
a supply level and bounces downwards, forming

128
00:11:28,492 --> 00:11:32,942
a red Heiken Ashi candle, ideally with no
upper shadows.

129
00:11:32,942 --> 00:11:38,042
You would put a stop loss order right below
the demand area when you are long in the market.

130
00:11:38,042 --> 00:11:42,532
Conversely, put your stop loss order right
above the supply area.

131
00:11:42,532 --> 00:11:47,282
The most common approach is to hold your trades
until the price action reaches an opposite

132
00:11:47,282 --> 00:11:48,752
level on the chart.

133
00:11:48,752 --> 00:11:53,892
So, if you are trading long a demand level,
you should hold your trade until the price

134
00:11:53,892 --> 00:11:56,792
action reaches the next supply zone on the
chart.

135
00:11:56,792 --> 00:12:03,042
Or you could close a part of your position
after a Heiken Ashi color change.

136
00:12:03,042 --> 00:12:07,112
How to define a trend using supply and demand
and heiken ashi

137
00:12:07,112 --> 00:12:12,352
Since we are primarily working with supply
and demand imbalances on Heiken ashi chart,

138
00:12:12,352 --> 00:12:17,832
making a higher high or a lower low does not
necessarily mean the existing trend will continue.

139
00:12:17,832 --> 00:12:20,362
Here’s my PRO TIP.
1.

140
00:12:20,362 --> 00:12:27,302
In an UPTREND: demand areas are being respected,
supply areas are being taken out.

141
00:12:27,302 --> 00:12:31,592
So a higher high SHOULD remove previous supply
to validate the demand zone

142
00:12:31,592 --> 00:12:32,792
2.

143
00:12:32,792 --> 00:12:39,402
In a DOWNTREND: supply areas are being respected,
demand areas are being taken out.

144
00:12:39,402 --> 00:13:15,372
A lower low SHOULD remove previous demand
to validate the supply zone.

145
00:13:15,372 --> 00:13:19,743
This type of analysis will help you a lot
in defining the strongest Heiken ashi supply

146
00:13:19,743 --> 00:13:21,432
or demand zones.

147
00:13:21,432 --> 00:13:26,642
• In a downtrend: supply areas are consistently
respected and demand areas are taken out

148
00:13:26,642 --> 00:13:32,412
• In an uptrend: supply areas are taken
out, while demand areas are respected

149
00:13:32,412 --> 00:13:34,282
AS SIMPLE AS THAT.

150
00:13:34,282 --> 00:13:39,572
And another tip is to look at your D1 or H4
chart and see what is going on with the supply

151
00:13:39,572 --> 00:13:43,802
and demand areas in control and decide which
direction to trade.

152
00:13:43,802 --> 00:13:48,882
Once you know what direction you want to go,
locate lower timeframe supply or demand areas

153
00:13:48,882 --> 00:13:53,742
with a strong move away, little time at the
level and also a fresh level.

154
00:13:53,742 --> 00:13:59,032
Now, it’s important to understand that there
can be several periods of accumulation during

155
00:13:59,032 --> 00:14:03,592
an uptrend and several periods of distribution
during downtrends.

156
00:14:03,592 --> 00:14:08,742
This means that there are supply and demand
reversal patterns and supply and demand continuation

157
00:14:08,742 --> 00:14:10,092
patterns.

158
00:14:10,092 --> 00:14:13,452
The Drop-Base-Rally is a bullish reversal
pattern

159
00:14:13,452 --> 00:14:17,552
The Rally-Base-Drop is a bearish reversal
pattern

160
00:14:17,552 --> 00:14:20,662
The Rally-Base-Rally is a bullish continuation
pattern

161
00:14:20,662 --> 00:14:26,202
The Drop-Base-Drop is a bearish continuation
pattern

162
00:14:26,202 --> 00:14:31,072
This is important because understanding which
phase the market is in, what is the underlying

163
00:14:31,072 --> 00:14:36,842
trend and how long has it been in place, determines
which are the best demand and supply zones

164
00:14:36,842 --> 00:14:38,181
to look for.

165
00:14:38,181 --> 00:14:41,512
In an old trend, you will want to look for
reversals.

166
00:14:41,512 --> 00:14:45,302
In a new trend you will want to look for continuations.

167
00:14:45,302 --> 00:15:32,952
You search for Rally-Base-Rally zones during
uptrends and for Drop-Base-Drop during downtrends.

168
00:15:32,952 --> 00:15:38,052
And remember that every timeframe has its
own trend and multiple trends coexist.

169
00:15:38,052 --> 00:15:42,842
You may be trading in an uptrend on H1, but
the D1 is in a downtrend

170
00:15:42,842 --> 00:15:48,602
So, the first thing you need to do is to decide
the time frames you will be using for a multiple

171
00:15:48,602 --> 00:15:50,752
timeframe analysis of the trend.

172
00:15:50,752 --> 00:15:53,272
You need at least 2 time frames.

173
00:15:53,272 --> 00:15:57,882
When several timeframes are combined to evaluate
a market, you will easily improve the odds

174
00:15:57,882 --> 00:16:02,772
of success for your supply and demand trades,
regardless of the other rules applied.

175
00:16:02,772 --> 00:16:07,612
This alone lowers risk as there is a higher
probability that price action will eventually

176
00:16:07,612 --> 00:16:10,712
continue on the longer trend.

177
